               <msContents>
                  <summary>A work on Sufi spiritual life by Ḥusayn ibn ‘Alim ibn Ḥasan al-Ḥusaynī (d. 1318), known as <addName>Amir Ḥusainī</addName> or <addName>Fakhr al-Sādāt</addName>. 
                     It is in mixed prose and poetry, interspersed with stories and sayings of the holy men. 
                     Divided into twenty-eight chapters, the text provides guidance to spiritual traveller in various stages in the path to purity. 
                     It commences with an panegyric preface that praises God, the Prophet Muhammad, and the first four Caliphs. 
                     
                     In the final chapter, the author states that he completed the work in in <date>711 AH ()</date>711, when 40 years old:
                     در ختم کتاب ای شب گرد بدروز سال عمرت بچهل رسیده و تو از جهل خود نارسیده... در شهور سنه احدی عشر و سبعماته مشاطه نشاط فکر بر بساط گردن و گوش هر یک را بزیور فصاحت و بلاغت مقرط و موشح گردانید 
                     It has been a popular Sufi work, widely copied and received several commentaries.</summary>
